<p><b>Graham Hurley</b>, born in 1946 at <a href="/wiki/Clacton-on-Sea" title="Clacton-on-Sea">Clacton on Sea</a>, is an <a href="/wiki/English_people" title="English people">English</a> <a href="/wiki/Crime_fiction" title="Crime fiction">crime fiction</a> writer.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Formerly based in <a href="/wiki/Portsmouth" title="Portsmouth">Portsmouth</a> but now relocated in the West Country, he is best known for creating the character of DI Joe Faraday, following several standalone novels. He contributed a column to <i><a href="/wiki/The_News_(Portsmouth)" title="The News (Portsmouth)">The Portsmouth News</a></i>. He received both a BA and an MA in English from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Cambridge" title="University of Cambridge">University of Cambridge</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>He worked as a script-writer with <a href="/wiki/Southern_Television" title="Southern Television">Southern Television</a> before becoming a researcher and later a director.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> He filmed the seabed wrecks of the Titanic and the Bismarck (with American oceanographer Robert Ballard) and produced ITV’s account of Richard Branson’s attempt to cross the Atlantic by balloon.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
